2.1.3) Jacobian matrix and Jacobian of
        an element¶

    

  

  

    

    

    

      
here x[i,j] is for $x_{j+1}^{(i+1)}$ coodinate

def J_matrix(x):
    return np.array([[x[0,0]-x[2,0], x[1,0]-x[2,0]],
                     [x[0,1]-x[2,1], x[1,1]-x[2,1]]])


            


          

        

      

    


  

  

    

      

        
In [7]:

        

          

            

              
def Je_matrix(i,coord,connect_python):
    coordinates_element = coord[connect_python[i]]
    Je_matrix = J_matrix(coordinates_element)
    return Je_matrix # returns the jacobian matrix of element i+1

def J_e(i,coord,connect_python):
    J_e=np.linalg.det(Je_matrix(i,coord,connect_python))
    return J_e # returns the jacobian of element i+1

2.1.4) Shape Functions¶

    

  

  

    

    

    

      
The function N(a,i) returs the value of the i-th shape function at the point $a=[a_0,a_1]$ in the reference
        element.


    

  

  

    

      

        
In [9]:

        

          

            

              
N,N1,N2,N3,a2,a1,a = symbols('N N1 N2 N3 a2 a1 a')

def N(a,i):
    a = [a1, a2]
    if i == 0 :
        N = a[0]
    if i == 1 :
        N = a[1]
    if i == 2 :
        N = 1 - a[0] - a[1]
    return N

N1 = N(a,0)
N2 = N(a,1)
N3 = N(a,2)
    
print('For node (1), shape function is : N1(a) =', N(a,0))
print('For node (2), shape function is : N2(a) =', N(a,1))
print('For node (3), shape function is : N3(a) =', N(a,2))

N = ([N1, N2, N3])
print('N(a)=',N)


            


          

        

      

    


    



      


        



          



          

            
For node (1), shape function is : N1(a) = a1
For node (2), shape function is : N2(a) = a2
For node (3), shape function is : N3(a) = -a1 - a2 + 1
N(a)= [a1, a2, -a1 - a2 + 1]

3.1.2) [$B_e$] matrix¶

    

  

  

    

      

        
In [16]:

        

          

            

              
def Be_matrix(x,L,H):
    return (4/(L*H))*np.array([[x[1,1]-x[2,1],0,x[2,1]-x[0,1],0,x[0,1]-x[1,1],0],
                     [0,x[2,0]-x[1,0],0,x[0,0]-x[2,0],0,x[1,0]-x[0,0]],
                     [x[2,0]-x[1,0],x[1,1]-x[2,1],x[0,0]-x[2,0],x[2,1]-x[0,1],x[1,0]-x[0,0],x[0,1]-x[1,1]]])


            


          

        

      

    


  

  

    

      

        
In [17]:

        

          

            

              
def Be(i,coord,connect_python,L,H):
    coord_element = coord[connect_python[i]]
    Be = Be_matrix(coord_element,L,H)
    return Be # returns the [B_e] at a given point of the reference element i+1

# we print results for each element 
for i in range(len(connect_python)):

    print(f"This is the [B_e] matrix of the element {i+1} : ")

Numerical application 3.2 :
        Elementary stiffness matrix¶

    

  

  

    

    

    

      
First we define the elasticity matrix [A]


    

  

  

    

      

        
In [18]:

        

          

            

              
def A(lamda,mu):
    return np.array([[lamda+2*mu, lamda, 0],
                     [lamda, lamda+2*mu, 0],
                     [0,   0,           mu]])


            


          

        

      

    


  

  

    

      

        
In [19]:

        

          

            

              
#[K_e] is the element stiffness matrix for element i+1
def K_e(i,coord,connect_python,lamda,mu,L,H):
    K_e =0.5*((Be(i,coord,connect_python,L,H).transpose())@A(lamda,mu)@Be(i,coord,connect_python,L,H))*J_e(i,coord,connect_python)
    return K_e

# same for each element 
def f_v(rho,L,H):
    g=9.81
    f_v = np.array([0, -(L*H*g*rho)/8, 0, -(L*H*g*rho)/8,0,0])
    return f_v

# surface force only applied in element 7 and 8  
def f_s(p,L):
    f_s = ((-p*L)/4)*np.array([0,0,0,1,0,1])
    return f_s

def L_e(i,connect_python):
    L_e=np.zeros([ne*D,Nn*D])
    for j in range(ne):
        k=connect_python[i,j]
        L_e[(2*(j+1)-1)-1,2*k]=1
        L_e[(2*(j+1))-1,2*k+1]=1
    return L_e

def K(coord,connect_python,lamda,mu,L,H) :
    K=np.zeros([Nn*D,Nn*D])
    for i in range(len(connect_python)):
        K=K+((L_e(i,connect_python).transpose())@K_e(i,coord,connect_python,lamda,mu,L,H)@L_e(i,connect_python))
    return K

def Fv(connect_python,rho,L,H) :
    Fv=np.zeros([Nn*D,])
    for i in range(len(connect_python)):
        Fv=Fv+((L_e(i,connect_python).transpose())@f_v(rho,L,H))
    return Fv

# we have a surface force only in element 8 an 7 
def Fs(connect_python,p,L) :
    Fs=np.zeros([Nn*D,])
    for i in [6,7]:
        Fs=Fs+((L_e(i,connect_python).transpose())@f_s(p,L))
    return Fs

# K_bc= global K matrix with boundary conditions 
# F_bc= global vector F with boundary conditions 
K_bc=K(coord,connect_python,lamda,mu,L,H) 
F_bc=F
for i in [5,11,12,14,16,17]: #(global dof)-1 because of python indexing
    K_bc[:,i]=0
    K_bc[i,:]=0
    K_bc[i,i]=1
    F_bc[i]= 0

        Numerical application 6 : Modification of the boundary condition at the bottom of the
        structure¶
      

    

  

  

    

    

    

      
We add two bondary conditions as the surface at $x_2$ = 0 is embedded.


    

  

  

    

      

        
In [34]:

        

          

            

              
# K_bc6= global K matrix with new boundary conditions 
# F_bc6= global vector F with new boundary conditions 
K_bc6=K(coord,connect_python,lamda,mu,L,H) 
F_bc6=F
for i in [4,5,10,11,12,14,16,17]: #(global dof)-1 because of python indexing
    K_bc6[:,i]=0
    K_bc6[i,:]=0
    K_bc6[i,i]=1
    F_bc6[i]= 0
    
# U_6 :  global nodal displacement vector with new boundary conditions 
U_6= np.linalg.solve(K_bc6,F_bc6)

# we reshape U_6 in order to have it as a coordinate matrix
U_coord_6=np.reshape(U_6, (9,2))

# U_F_6: coordinates of the deformed mesh 
U_F_6=(coeff*U_coord_6)+coord

# Plot of the deformed mesh
plt.figure(2,figsize=([6.4, 4.8]),dpi=300)
meshplot(coord,connect_python)
for i in connect_python :
        plt.plot(U_F_6[i][:,0] , U_F_6[i][:,1] , "ro-")
plt.title('Deformed shape in red')
plt.savefig("deformed_shape_6.png",dpi=500)
plt.show()
